\begin_layout Standard
One dimensional discrete QW is quantum version of the classical random walk.
 The walker is described by two internal states (denoted by
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\uparrow\right\rangle ,\left|\downarrow\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and the position state (labeled as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

), and the internal state and the position state can be coupled through
 the coin operation 
\begin_inset Formula $R(\theta,x)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the control parameter and it may dependent on the position of the walker
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

).
 We focus on the split-step quantum walk (SSQW) and its one-step floquet
 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2})$
\end_inset

 is defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U(\theta_{1},\theta_{2}) & = & S_{+}R(\theta_{2})S_{-}R(\theta_{1})\label{eq:1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\pm}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum|i\pm1\rangle\langle i|\otimes|\uparrow\rangle\left\langle \uparrow\left|+1\otimes\right|\downarrow\right\rangle \langle\downarrow|$
\end_inset

 and 
